    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Obesity in Children</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michelle Garland letter attributes obesity in children to decline in walking (Oct 19 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''While Children Grow Fatter, Experts Search for Solutions'' (front page, Oct. 19):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''While Children Grow Fatter, Experts Search for Solutions'' (front page, Oct. 19):</p>
        <p>Your article reports that physical inactivity is one component driving the increased rate of obesity in children. A study by my group comparing rates of walking to the number of overweight children found that walking, the most basic physical activity, has declined by 37 percent since 1977 while the number of overweight children increased by 75 percent in the same period.</p>
        <p>Children used to walk. But today, because of the way communities have been built, they can't walk to their destinations. Instead, parents must drive them. As a result, moms and dads have become chauffeurs, and children have become fat.</p>
        <p>MICHELLE GARLAND  Washington, Oct. 19, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an analyst, Surface Transportation Policy Project.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
